  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in many countries around the world. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. Key elements typically include:\n\n1. Requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\n2. Major regulatory frameworks include:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (USA)\n- EU Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n\n3. Regulations cover various financial sectors:\n- Banks\n- Credit unions\n- Investment firms\n- Money transfer services\n- Cryptocurrency exchanges\n\n4. Penalties for non-compliance can include:\n- Substantial financial fines\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Loss of business licenses\n\n5. Global cooperation exists to track and prevent money laundering across international borders.\n\nThese regulations aim to detect and prevent financial crimes like money laundering, terrorist financing, and other illegal financial activities.",
